WINE QUALITY DATASETS¶

Project on Machine Learning Algorithm¶

         Wine Quality Predictions

PROBLEM STATEMENT:¶

OBJECTIVE 1: To make use of wine quality data and to create clusters/groups based on similarities between them(Unsupervised learning).

OBJECTIVE 2: To make use of wine quality data and predict the quality of wine(Supervised learning).

PROBLEM FEATURE:¶

The datasets contains various features/ columns regarding the content, density, colour etc. of the wine based on which they are grouped into few homogeneous categories by using unsupervised learning ML algorithms. Later on, supervised ML algorithms are used to predict the goodness feature of the wine. Evaluation metrics intended to use in this classificatio problem are as follows. 1) Accuracy 2) F1 Score.

FEATURE ENGINEERING:¶

Analysis of data using various plots like scatter,regression bar,etc. to identify trends or patterns between and among dependent and independent variables. Scaling or standardization of feature values for unsupervised learning. One-hot-encoding of categorical columns.

In this JUPYTER NOTEBOOK i have done with the data visualization

In [5]:
def check_missing_data(wine_quality):
    flag=wine_quality.isna().sum().any()
    if flag==True:
        total = wine_quality.isnull().sum()
        percent = (wine_quality.isnull().sum())/(wine_quality.isnull().count()*100)
        output = pd.concat([total, percent], axis=1, keys=['Total', 'Percent'])
        data_type = []
        for col in wine_quality.columns:
            dtype = str(wine_quality[col].dtype)
            data_type.append(dtype)
        output['Types'] = data_type
        return(np.transpose(output))
    else:
        return(False)
    
check_missing_data(wine_quality)

#function for missing data
def missing_value(wine_quality):
    total = wine_quality.isnull().sum().sort_values(ascending=False)
    percent = (wine_quality.isnull().sum()/wine_quality.isnull().count()).sort_values(ascending=False)
    missing_data = pd.concat([total, percent], axis=1, keys=['Total', 'Percent'])
    return(missing_data.head(20))
missing_value(wine_quality)

HERE IN THIS CORRELATION MATRIX ,THERE IS HIGH CORRELATION BETWEEN GOOD AND QUALITY VARIBLES - 0.76

it is found that 'quality' column is highly correlated to 'good'column as previously determined by countplot. Besides, correlation between 'free sulfur dioxide' and 'total sulfur dioxide' is also high. Thus it is logical to remove one among them to reduce redundancy. Since , 'free sulfur dioxide' is part of the 'total sulfur dioxide' , lets remove 'free sulfur dioxide
